TY  - JOUR
T1  - Pay Equality and Industrial Politics
AU  - Lazear, Edward P.
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261616
DO  - 10.1086/261616
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 561
EP  - 580
VL  - 97
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Personnel managers often argue that equitable pay treatment manifested as wage compression is useful because it reduces disharmony among workers. But it is far from obvious that a compressed salary structure is morale improving since better workers may feel disenchanted by this scheme. However, when workers' rewards are based on relative comparisons, salary compression reduces uncooperative behavior that is detrimental to the firm. Relative comparisons imply that some reference group must be selected. The major result is that within the relevant groups, some wage compression is efficient.
AB  - Personnel managers often argue that equitable pay treatment manifested as wage compression is useful because it reduces disharmony among workers. But it is far from obvious that a compressed salary structure is morale improving since better workers may feel disenchanted by this scheme. However, when workers' rewards are based on relative comparisons, salary compression reduces uncooperative behavior that is detrimental to the firm. Relative comparisons imply that some reference group must be selected. The major result is that within the relevant groups, some wage compression is efficient.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261616
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261616
Y2  - 2024/03/22
